{
  "texts": [
    "At the time of running our experiment, the pay-as-you-go tier with up to 10,000 requests per day has been announced, but is not yet available 21.After some instruction-tuning on sampled web documents from CC, we adopted the following query: Document: \"'{cc_web_document}\"' Question: Does the document enclosed in triple quotes contain geographic coordinates, such as a latitude-longitude pair, or a street address that can be used to identify a physical location such as a building?",
    "If so, return a few examples.",
    "If not, just say 'None'.We assume the web documents do not contain adverse instructions that may confuse the language model.",
    "Initially, we wanted to use separate queries for coordinates and street addresses; however, due to the API limitations, we decided to combine both elements into a single query to half the execution time after confirming that Gemini responds with both categories of examples (coordinates, addresses) where both are present in the document.The examples of Gemini responses for queries with documents containing (1) both an address and coordinates, ( 2 Determining sample sizePrevious studies that analysed CC have done so on many randomly sampled documents (often an arbitrary, but large and round number).",
    "For example, Luccioni and Viviano [18] sampled 1% of the English language documents in a single CC release, which amounted to just under 6 million documents."
  ]
}